Information

Jupiter's Geography Jupiter is 1.90 × 10^27 kg (318 Earths.) The Equatorial Diameter is 142,984 km and the Polar Diameter is 133,709 km. It is 483.8 million mi from the sun and 365 million miles (588 million kilometers) away from earth.


Information about Jupiter Jupiter is the second largest planet in our Solar System. It is the fourth brigestest plaent in the solar system as well. The days are 9 hours and 55 minuets, making them the shortest days on any planet. Jupiter has a total of 67 moons, but the four that are most know are Io, Europa, Ganymede and Callisto. The surface temperature is -108 degrees Celcius!


Jupiter and it's Roman God. Believe it or not, Jupiter's Roman god equilavent is Jupiter. Jupiter (the god, also called Zeus in Greek) is said to be the king of the gods. He is the god of the sky. In actaul Roman his name is commenly Jove.He is said to be the father of all Roman gods except for his own parents. Jupiter was the father of Vulcan, Venus, Minerva, Apollo, Diana, Mercury, Bacchus, Mars and Proserpina. The sisters of Jupiter were Vesta, Juno and Ceres.The brothers of Jupiter were Pluto, and Neptune


The giant red spot you may see of the surface of Jupiter is an extremely large storm that has been going on for 300 years. The storm is so big that three earths could fit inside.Jupiter's magnetic field is around 14 times stronger than earth's.It may not be clear but, Jupiter has a ring around it, dust makes it so the ring is hard to see from just about any telescope.The first recorded sighting of Jupiter were by the ancient Babylonians in around 7th or 8th BC. It is named for Jupiter, the king of the Roman gods and god of the Sky.
